I have been trying to take a deep look at Justice Stephen Breyer, who is 82. He is the most likely to resign this year to avoid an election year (grant it mid-term elections) RBG situation and ensure that a liberal is appointed in his place. The major question is, how is his health? I cannot find anything regarding his health. Reviewing his caseload, it appears to be pretty steady and he has hired a full slate of law clerks for the next term, which suggests that he plans to be around for the remainder of the year. However, there is significant pressure from Democrats and progressives for Breyer to step down out of fear of loosing the Senate in the mid-terms, which history supports is very possible. At this time, I have no reason to believe that Breyer will step down this year. The next oldest justices are Thomas (72) and Alito (71). I do not see either one of them going anywhere anytime soon, especially under a Democratic Administration, with the exception of suddenly passing away. The rumors of Justice Sotomayor having some underlining health condition that might result in her stepping down has never been supported by any evidence and appears to have just been a Trump Administration rumor. For now, I am maintaining my forecast, but will be following Breyer involvement in court activities over the next month, mainly how many opinions he pens.

Assumes exponential distribution of vacancies per year with Poisson arrival rate. Previous forecasts tuned lambda based on the average age across the entire court (using vacancy data beginning in 1980). I discovered that the sum of the age of the two oldest justices was much more correlated with vacancy arrivals, so I'm switching to that.

For the most recent 30 years of its history, the Supreme Court has averaged a vacancy every 3.3 years. To make a good prediction for the current court, politics must be considered. So here we go: -Only 1 justice (Breyer) is "old" by SCOTUS standards. Having been a Clinton appointee, he could theoretically retire during the Biden administration without altering the balance. I see no reason that he would retire from the court prior to the end of the year. -Sotomayor (Obama), Kagan (Obama), Gorsuch (Trump), Kavanaugh (Trump), Coney Barrett (Trump), and Roberts (Bush) are all considered young by SCOTUS standards. -Alito (Bush), Thomas (Bush the elder), both traditionalists have no incentive to leave the court during the Biden administration. -Finally, adding justices to the court...what is being called "court packing" in the media, will not happen this year. Although the majority of democrats would love to balance the Supreme Court, in the end it will be a political decision (not to mention that it would set a bad precedent... one co-equal branch of government altering another with very shaky Constitutional authority?). Some may disagree on this point...but the bottom line is that it will not happen in year one unless legislative and executive priorities change drastically.

This one is very interesting and involves lots of layers. Let start with the big picture. The average justice since 1900 serves an average of 26 years on the bench. The average of justices who choose to retire is about 74 years old. Five of the last eight President's had a vacancy in their first year in office. This includes the last two Democratic Presidents who were boosted by a retirement during their first year (1993 and 2009). The overall rate of a vaccancy is one about ever 2.06 years. Based on this, there are two Justices who are likely on retirement watch, Justice Thomas and Justice Breyer. Justice Thomas is extremely unlikely to retire. An opening of his seat would likely be due to health issues although that does not appear to be an immediate concern. Justice Breyer however will be under extreme pressure to retire during the next two years. Although the Senate map is favorable in 2022, Liberal democrats will likely not want to take the risk and will apply pressure on Breyer during the next 12 months. Will he be receptive? I think he will be more than perhaps a year ago given the RGB seat and the general politics of the day. It could be interesting to wathc his votes and opinions during the Spring term for any hints of his thinking.

I figure the real death chance is rather lower than the SSA actuarial tables (better health care and living conditions than average, 1/12th the year already passed), while the chance Breyer will resign to arrange his replacement between Supreme Court terms while the Democrats have a Senate majority then pushes up the odds a little (but he's likely thinking "next year" on that, even though it ups the risk of a Senate D being replaced by an R).

I looked at the number of confirmed judges between 1945 and 2020 (took this as a proxy for vacancies at the court). There where 33 vacancies in 75 jears giving a 44% change of a vacancy in any given year. This included both retirement and death. Lowered the change to 40 since the 6 conservative judges wont be likely to retire with a democrat in the white house. Also took into consideration that life expectancy has increased considerably since 1945.

I think it is more likely than not there will be no vacancies in 2021. The Court is relatively young and appear to be in good health. At 82, Justice Breyer is the oldest of the nine Justices, and though there may be some pressure for him to retire and allow his spot to be filled by someone younger with similar political leanings, he may not be in a hurry to step down. The Court has undergone significant change over the past few years, and Breyer may want to remain on the Court to lend it stability. If he delayed his retirement until 2022, his seat could still be filled by the Biden administration. There is a chance he will retire in 2021, but I think it is more likely he'll try to wait.

Justice Breyer is the most likely to step down, but it is more likely he would do so in the second year of the Biden administration. I doubt that the number of Supreme Court seats will be increased given there will certainly be opposition from Republicans and moderate Democrats. The outlier is the unexpected death of a justice but none currently seem to have serious health problems.

Justice Breyer is statistically the most likely vacancy. Would he consider vacating his seat to ensure President Biden can nominate before the mid-terms? My guess is not this year, unless he were to become ill. I cannot see any of the Republican appointees vacating, and Justices Kagan and Sotomayor are still relatively young. The obvious outlier is whether President Biden's commission recommends increasing the number of justices. Whilst court packing is popular some circles, it seems slightly counterproductive - the 'other side' can simply do the same and the court quickly gets too big. To get the 'balance' desired 4 new justices would be required (leading to 13 - perhaps someone superstitious might not like that!). For now I am suggesting this is unlikely. However, as the commission gets going, I am sure more information will leak and we can reassess.
